 11 Matrices as transformations 11.1 Linear Transformations 11.1.1 Def “linear transformation” A linear transformation from \(\mathbb{R}^m\) to \(\mathbb{R}^n\) is \(L: \mathbb{R}^m ightarrow \mathbb{R}^n\) such that for each \(\vec{x}, \vec{y} \in \mathbb{R}^m, L(\vec{x} + \vec{y}) = L(\vec{x}) + L(\vec{y})\) for each \(\lambda \in \mathbb{R}\) and each \(\vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^m, L(\lambda\vec{x}) = \lambda L(\vec{x})\) Example 1 \(L: \mathbb{R} ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) is a linear transformation. For each \(x \in \mathbb{R}, L(x) = L(1x) = xL(1)\) \[\Rightarrow x\in \mathbb{R}, L(x) = cx.\] Other examples omitted. See paper notes. 11.1.2 Prop 1 “linear transformation properties” Let \(L: \mathbb{R}^m ightarrow \mathbb{R}^n\) be a linear transformation. Then \(L(\vec{0}) = \vec{0}\) If \(X = \{\vec{x}_1, ..., \vec{x}_k\} \subseteq \mathbb{R}^m\) is linearly dependent, then \(L(X)\) is linearly dependent. \(L\) is injective if and only if \(L(\vec{x}) = \vec{0} \Rightarrow \vec{x} = \vec{0}\) \(L\) is surjective if and only if \(span(\{L(\vec{e}_1), ..., L(\vec{e}_m)\}) = \mathbb{R}^n\) 11.1.2.1 Term “matrix representation” of \(L\) For each \(L: \mathbb{R} ightarrow \mathbb{R}\), linear transformation, there exists a unique \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes m}\) such that \[L(\vec{x}) = A \vec{x},  orall \vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^m.\] We call \(A\) the matrix representation of \(L\). 11.1.3 Prop 2 “invertible iff bijective” Suppose \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{m 	imes n}\) is the matrix representation of \(L: \mathbb{R}^m ightarrow \mathbb{R}^n\). The \(A\) is invertible if and only if \(L\) is bijective. 11.1.4 Def “eigenvector” An eigenvector of \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) is a vector \(\vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n\) with \(\vec{x} 
eq \vec{0}\) such that \(A\vec{x} = \lambda \vec{x}\) for some \(\lambda \in \mathbb{R}\). \(\lambda\) is the eigenvalue for \(\vec{x}\). Example 8 \[ A =  egin{bmatrix} 0 \ . \ . \ . \ a_{ii} . \ . \ . \ 0 \end{bmatrix} = a_{ii}\vec{e}_i \] NOT FINISHED Example 9 \[A =  egin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 \ 1 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix}\] \[A - \lambda Id^2 =  egin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 \ 1 &amp; 1 \end{bmatrix} +  egin{bmatrix} -\lambda &amp; 0 \ 0 &amp; -\lambda \end{bmatrix} =  egin{bmatrix} -\lambda &amp; 1 \ 1 &amp; 1 - \lambda \end{bmatrix}\] Next, \[\det( egin{bmatrix} -\lambda &amp; 1 \ 1 &amp; 1 - \lambda \end{bmatrix}) = -\lambda(1-\lambda) - 1 = -\lambda + \lambda^2 - 1 \Rightarrow \lambda =  rac{1 \pm \sqrt{5}}{2}\] Solving this system of equations eventually shows \(x_1 =  rac{\sqrt{5} - 1}{2}, x_2 = 1\) 11.1.4.1 Notice: If 0 is an eigenvalue: \[0 = det(A - \lambda Id^n) = det(A)\] 11.1.5 Prop 4 “invertible iff eigenvalue nonzero” A matrix \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) is invertible if and only if 0 is not one of its eigenvalues. 11.2 Quadratic Forms 11.2.1 Def “quadratic forms” A quadratic form is a mapping \(q: \mathbb{R}^n ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) such that \[q(\vec{x}) = \sum_{i=1}^n\sum_{j=1}^n a_{ij}x_i x_j\] if n=1: \(q(\vec{x} = x_1) = a_{11}x_1^2\) if n=2: \(q(\vec{x}) = a_{11}x_1^2 + a_{12}x_1 x_2 + a_{21}x_1 x_2 + a_{12}x_2^2\) properties when \(n=1\): if \(a_{11} &gt; 0\) then \(q(x_1)&gt;0  orall x_1 
eq 0\) and \(q(x_1) \geq 0  orall x\) if \(a_{11} &lt; 0\) then \(q(x_1)&lt;0  orall x_1 
eq 0\) and \(q(x_1) \leq 0  orall x\) 11.2.2 Def “quadratic positive/negative” the quadratic form \(q: \mathbb{R}^n ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) is positive (resp negative) definite if \(q(\vec{x})&gt;0\) for all \(\vec{x} 
eq \vec{0}\) positive (resp negative) semi-definite if \(q(\vec{x}) \geq 0\) for all \(\vec{x}\) indefinite if there exists \(\vec{x}, \vec{y}\) s.t. \(q(\vec{x}) &lt; 0\) and \(q(\vec{y}) &gt; 0\) 11.2.3 Prop 5 “unique symmetric matrix” Let \(q: \mathbb{R}^n ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) be a quadratic form. There exists a unique symmetric matrix \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) such that for each \(\vec{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n\) \[q(\vec{x}) = \vec{x}^T A \vec{x}.\] 11.2.4 Prop 6 “eigenvalues pos \(\iff\) pos def” Let \(q(\vec{x}) = \vec{x}^T A \vec{x}\) be a quadratic form. \(A\) MUST ALSO BE SYMMETRIC! \(q\) (or \(A\)) is positive (resp. negative) definite if and only if all of its eigenvalues are strictly positive (negative) \(q\) (or \(A\)) is positive (resp. negative) semidefinite if and only if all of its eigenvalues are \(\geq 0\) (\(\leq 0\)). 11.2.4.1 Corollary Fix \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\). if \(A\) is positive (negative) definite, it is invertible. if \(A\) is positive (negative) definite, \(A^{-1}\) is also positive (negative) definite if \(A\) is positive (negative) semidefinite, but not definite, then \(A\) is NOT invertible. 11.2.5 Prop 7 “pos/neg \(\iff\) leading principal minor” Fix \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\). \(A\) MUST ALSO BE SYMMETRIC! \(A\) is positive definite if and only if, for each \(r= 1, ..., n\), the leading principal minor of order \(r\) is strictly positive. \(A\) is positive semi-definite if and only if, for each \(r= 1, ..., n\), each principal minor of order \(r\) is greater than or equal to zero. \(A\) is negative definite if and only if, for each \(r= 1, ..., n\), the leading principal minor of order \(r\) has sign \((-1)^r\). \(A\) is negative semi-definite if and only if, for each \(r= 1, ..., n\), each principal minor of order \(r\) either has sign \((-1)^n\) or is zero. 11.2.5.0.1 Begin Class 10 - 2023-08-25 11.2.5.1 Term “lower triangle matrix” \(A\) is a lower triangle matrix if \(a_{ij} = 0\) when \(i&lt;j\) 11.2.6 Thm “Cholesky Decomposition” Let \(A \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) symmetric matrix. If \(A\) is positive definite, there exists a unique invertible lower triangle matrix \(B \in \mathbb{R}^{n 	imes n}\) such that \(A = BB^T\). We call \(B\) the Cholesky Decomposition of \(A\).

 12 Convexity 12.1 Convex Sets 12.1.1 Def “convex” Let \(X \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n\) be non-empty. Call \(X\) convex if, for each \(\vec{x}, \vec{y} \in X\) and each \(\alpha \in [0,1], \alpha \vec{x} + (1-\alpha) \vec{y} \in X\). Example 1 \(X \subseteq \mathbb{R}\). \(X\) is convex iff \(X\) is an interval. Proof “showing \(X\) is convex \(\Rightarrow X\) is an interval” Fix an interval \(I \subseteq \mathbb{R}\) and look at \(x, y \in I\). without loss of generality, suppose \(x \geq y\) fix \(\alpha \in [0,1]\). note \[x \geq \alpha x + (1-\alpha) y \geq y \Rightarrow \alpha x + (1-\alpha) y \in I \Rightarrow I 	ext{ is convex.}\] “showing \(X\) is convex \(\Leftarrow X\) is an interval” will show: contrapositive (if \(X\) is not an interval \(\Rightarrow X\) is not convex.) Example 1 See drawings. Convex sets: Not-convex sets: 12.1.2 Prop 1 “convex operations” Let \(X_1, X_2\) be nonempty convex sets (applies for any finite number of sets) \(X_1 \cap X_2\) is convex or empty for each \(\lambda_1, \lambda_2 \in \mathbb{R}\) we have \(\lambda_1 X_1 + \lambda_2 X_2 = \{\lambda_1 \vec{x}_1 + \lambda_2 \vec{x}_2: \vec{x}_1 \in X_1, \vec{x}_2 \in X_2\}\) is convex \(X_1 	imes X_2\) is convex. All of \(\mathbb{R}^2\) is convex! 12.1.3 Def “convex combination” A vector \(\vec{x}\in\mathbb{R}^n\) is a convex combination of \(\{\vec{x_1}, ..., \vec{x_k}\}\) if there exists \(\alpha_1, ..., \alpha_k, \alpha_k \in [0,1]\) such that \[\sum_{k=1}^K \alpha_k = 1 	ext{ and } \vec{x} = \sum_{k=1}^K \alpha_k \vec{x_k}\] Note: “a convex combination is a linear combination”, but this requires the condition (that the \(\alpha_k\)’s sum to 1 which a linear combination did not) 12.1.4 Def “convex hull” Fix \(X \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n\), nonempty. The convex hull of \(X\) is the set of convex combinations of some finite \(\hat{X} \subseteq X\). Denoted \(conv(X)\). Note: \(conv(X)\) gives you the minimal convex set that contains \(X\) 12.1.5 Prop 2 “convex hull is convex” Fix \(X, Y \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n\), nonempty \(conv(X)\) is convex \(X\) is convex iff and only if \(X = conv(X)\) if \(X \subseteq Y, conv(X) \subseteq conv(Y)\) \(conv(X) = \cap \{C \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n: C 	ext{is convex and } X \subseteq C\}\) 12.2 Concave vs Convex Functions 12.2.0.1 Remember: we should always assume \(X\) is convex, even if we are not explicitly told \(X\) is convex 12.2.1 Def “convex and strictly convex functions” Fix \(f: X ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) \(f\) is convex if, for each \(\vec{x}, \vec{y} \in X\) and each \(\alpha \in [0,1]\) we have \(f(\alpha \vec{x} + (1- \alpha) \vec{y}) \leq \alpha f(\vec{x}) + (1- \alpha) f(\vec{y})\) \(f\) is strictly convex if, for each \(\vec{x}, \vec{y} \ in X\) and each \(\alpha \in (0,1)\) we have \(f(\alpha \vec{x} + (1- \alpha) \vec{y}) &lt; \alpha f(\vec{x}) + (1- \alpha) f(\vec{y})\) \(f\) is concave if, for each \(\vec{x}, \vec{y} \in X\) and each \(\alpha \in [0,1]\) we have \(f(\alpha \vec{x} + (1- \alpha) \vec{y}) \geq \alpha f(\vec{x}) + (1- \alpha) f(\vec{y})\) \(f\) is strictly concave if, for each \(\vec{x}, \vec{y} \ in X\) and each \(\alpha \in (0,1)\) we have \(f(\alpha \vec{x} + (1- \alpha) \vec{y}) &gt; \alpha f(\vec{x}) + (1- \alpha) f(\vec{y})\) a function can be convex and concave so long as it’s a line 12.2.1.1 Term “graph of f” \[Graph(f) = \{(\vec{x}, y) \in X 	imes \mathbb{R}: y = f(\vec{x})\}\] 12.2.1.2 Term “subgraph of f” \[sub(f) = \{(\vec{x}, y) \in X 	imes \mathbb{R}: y \leq f(\vec{x})\}\] 12.2.1.3 Term “epigraph of f” \[epi(f) = \{(\vec{x}, y) \in X 	imes \mathbb{R}: y \geq f(\vec{x})\}\] 12.2.1.4 Remember: \(epi(f) \cap sub(f) = graph(f)\) 12.2.2 Prop 3 “\(f\) convex \(\iff epi(f)\) convex” \(f: X ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) is convex if and only if \(epi(f)\) is a convex set \(f: X ightarrow \mathbb{R}\) is concave if and only if \(sub(f)\) is a convex set 12.2.3 Prop 4 if \(f\) and \(g\) are convex, \(f+g\) is convex if \(f\) and \(g\) are concave, \(f+g\) is concave if \(h\) is increasing and convex and \(f\) is convex, then \(h \circ f\) is convex if \(h\) is increasing and concave and \(f\) is concave, then \(h \circ f\) is concave if \(h\) is decreasing and concave and \(f\) is convex, then \(h \circ f\) is concave Example 4 \[ egin{aligned} f:&amp; \mathbb{R}_+ ightarrow \mathbb{R} 	ext{ such that } f(x) = \sqrt{x} \Rightarrow 	ext{ concave} \ g:&amp; \mathbb{R}_+ ightarrow \mathbb{R} 	ext{ such that } g(x) = x^2 \Rightarrow 	ext{ convex} \ h:&amp; \mathbb{R} ightarrow \mathbb{R} 	ext{ such that } h(x) = -x \Rightarrow 	ext{ both} \end{aligned}\] \(h(g(x)) = -x^2\) which is concave \(h(f(x)) = -\sqrt{x}\) which is convex 12.2.4 Claim A is positive definite if and only if \(f\) is strictly convex A is negative definite if and only if \(f\) is strictly concave A is positive semidefinite if and only if \(f\) is convex A is negative semidefinite if and only if \(f\) is concave Proof of positive definite claim Assume \(A\) is positive definite. Fix \(\vec{x} 
